# Diaphragm

> The diaphragm is a **dome-shaped musculotendinous partition** separating the thoracic and abdominal cavities. It is the **primary muscle of inspiration** (~70% of tidal volume) and also increases intra-abdominal pressure during Valsalva manoeuvres.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Respiratory System]], [[Muscular System]]
- Above (thoracic surface): [[Lungs]] / [[Pleura]], pericardium / heart
- Below (abdominal surface): [[Liver]] (right lobe), stomach, spleen
- Skeletal attachments: [[Lumbar Vertebrae]] (crura, L1–L3), [[Ribs]] 7–12 (costal), [[Sternum]] xiphoid process
- Innervation: **Phrenic nerve (C3, C4, C5)** — bilateral, motor + sensory to central tendon; intercostal nerves (T6–T12) — peripheral sensory only
- "C3, C4, C5 keep the diaphragm alive"

## 🔬 Structure

### Attachments (Origin)
| Part | Attachment |
|------|-----------|
| **Sternal part** | Xiphoid process (posterior surface) |
| **Costal part** | Inner surfaces of lower 6 ribs and costal cartilages |
| **Lumbar part (crura)** | Right crus: L1–L3; Left crus: L1–L2; Medial + lateral arcuate ligaments |

### Central Tendon
- Clover-shaped aponeurosis at dome apex; fused with pericardium above

### Three Major Openings (Mnemonic: **I 8 10 eggs at 12**)

| Opening | Level | Contents |
|---------|-------|----------|
| **Caval hiatus** | T8 | IVC + right phrenic nerve (IVC expands with inspiration → ↑ venous return) |
| **Oesophageal hiatus** | T10 | Oesophagus + left and right vagus nerves (CN X) + oesophageal branches of left gastric vessels |
| **Aortic hiatus** | T12 | Aorta + thoracic duct + azygos vein (aorta doesn't move with diaphragm) |

## ⚙️ Function
- **Inspiration** — diaphragm contracts and descends → increases thoracic volume → negative intrathoracic pressure → air flows in
- **Expiration** — diaphragm relaxes → elastic recoil of lungs → passive during quiet breathing; active muscles (abdominals, [[Rectus Abdominis]]) in forced expiration
- **Valsalva** — contracts simultaneously with abdominals → ↑ intra-abdominal pressure (defecation, urination, childbirth, lifting)
- **Cough / sneeze** — rapid contraction generates high expiratory flow

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Hiatus hernia** — oesophageal hiatus widening allows stomach herniation into thorax; sliding (90%) vs. para-oesophageal (10%); causes GORD
- **Phrenic nerve palsy** — unilateral (elevated hemidiaphragm on CXR) or bilateral (ventilatory failure); causes: neck surgery, lung cancer (left phrenic), cardiac surgery
- **Diaphragmatic hernia (congenital)** — Bochdalek (posterolateral, left); bowel in thorax → lung hypoplasia → neonatal emergency
- **Referred pain** — diaphragmatic irritation (pericarditis, subphrenic abscess, ectopic pregnancy) → shoulder tip pain (C4 dermatome — phrenic nerve)
- **Hiccup** — involuntary spasmodic diaphragm contraction; glottis closure → characteristic sound

